6mk.title: Geometry of vectors: direction
6mk.clickbait: What rotation would it take to line up this vector to this one?
6mk.text:
motivated by comparing vectors geometrically 

For vectors that are pointing in the same direction, it is easy to compare their relative magnitudes. We can determine which scalar is needed to convert one to the other. But for arbitrary vectors, we'll need a way to compare their directions. To compare the magnitudes of vectors pointing in different directions, we will also need to specify the geometry.


start with a simpler question, what does it take to bring magnitude of a to the magnitude of b?

ans: scale it by b/a

think of this as _doing_ something to the vector, scaling it, that will change one vector to another vector
scalar is what we need to do to one vector to get the other

now lets consider two vectors of the same magnitude, but with different directions

![two vectors a and b]()

What would it take to bring the direction of a to the direction of b?
It would take a rotation by a certain amount, called the angle (for which we usually use Greek letters, in particular $\theta$ and $\varphi$).

We can say that $a \measuredangle \theta = b$ - it's like scaling the vector a by the angle $\theta$.

Angles can be specified by what fraction of a circle they rotate by. A special number is used to represent one full rotation, called $2\pi$. This number is the circumference of a circle with radius 1. 

![circle with various angles marked]()

special angle that doesn't do anything - $1$

There's a special angle that reverses the direction of the vector. This angle actually _is_ a scalar, the scalar number $-1$. So we say that $-1 = \measuredangle \pi$. 

![180 degree angle]()

Another special angle that is one quarter of a full rotation. This angle is called a right angle. In drawings, we use a special mark for marking right angles.

![a right angle]()

When two vectors are at right angles, we say they are orthogonal (Greek for right-angular).

## Bivectors
Now if you've been paying close attention, you might have noticed that there is a slight problem. There are two equally valid right angles, and we can't fully describe the relationship between our vectors unless we know which right angle is meant.

![the two different right angles]()

This problem is even more obvious in three dimensions!

![lots of right angles in 3d]()

To accurately use angles, we need to specify which "direction" they are rotating in. But not the ordinary direction, a sort of two dimensional direction. 

We need a new type of object to represent this. We'll use a [bivector bivector]:

It is similar to a vector, having a magnitude (area), and a sort of direction - an orientation in two dimensions, along with a rotation direction. A bivector is also known as a 2-vector. 

Bivectors do not have a shape - meaning these are all the same bivector since the have the same magnitude, and are oriented in the same plane.

As a reference, we'll use the bivector $\text{I}$ which has magnitude 1.

We can scale $\text{I}$ by the angle to represent different rotations. Scaling by a negative amount reverses the direction.

So to fully describe what it takes to bring the direction of $a$ to the direction of $b$, we need the bivector, along with the angle (which scales the bivector). So we should write $a \measuredangle \text{I}\theta = b$ for our original example. We call $\measuredangle \text{I}\theta$ a rotor, since it rotates $a$ to $b$.

A more common way to write a rotor is like this: $a e^{\text{I}\theta} = b$. When we multiply two rotors with the same bivector, the angles add. $ae^{\text{I}\theta}e^{\text{I}\varphi}=ae^{\text{I}(\theta + \varphi)}$. Since this is the same rule as exponents, we use the same notation to remind us of that.

We do need to be careful about one thing though, the angles do not add when the rotors have bivectors with different orientations. So $ e^{\text{I}\theta}e^{\text{J}\varphi}$ is NOT the same as $e^{\text{I}\theta + \text{J}\varphi}$. The problem ultimately comes down to the fact that rotations are non-commutative - it matters what order you do them in.

![gif of non-commutative rotations of a cube]()

Another caveat is that the rotors we have now only work with vectors that lie within the bivector plane - it doesn't do what we would expect when the vector is pointing away from the plane. Later, we will see how to fix the rotors so that they work in all situations how we expect. 

![whoops i made a trivector pic? or is that too confusing...]()
